text: It is a copy of the funny guy scene in Goodfellas:  1. A seemingly casual conversation takes place about everyday stuff 2. The conversation takes a very serious turn where a guy thinks that what he just said might get him killed 3. The laugh and the "I had you moment" at the end  HOWEVER, with that said, the "copying" is VERY well done. And like Robert Altman said to Paul Thomas Anderson after Anderson told to Altman that "All I do is rip you off" when he makes movies, the only way you can steal someone's work is if you actually take someone's finished work, cross his name from the credits and write your own name over it. Everything else is inspiration and Scorsese has countless inspirations in his work. You can find dozens of videos here on Youtube where he talks about hundreds of movies that have inspired him throughout his life. If you want an example from GoodFellas, he openly states in one of the videos that De Niro's "acting with his eyes" while smoking a cigarette moment in GoodFellas was inspired by the acting style from the film The Tales of Hoffmann.  And speaking of GoodFellas, anyone else think that Depp both looks and sounds like Ray Liotta in the trailer. After Blow, I guess like father like son.

text: This trailer, taken of and by itself, is a great Short Film, called, Black Mass.¬† It is about this angel who comes to evaluate a candidate for the priesthood.¬† And it becomes readily apparent that this guy needs to seek another family, and not one that is connected to organized crime. For he who cannot keep a secret, should really be preaching the Gospel. "Behold, the Truth."¬† ...... (Now in real life, a psychiatrist would declare him psychotic, and unfit to stand trial.¬† "No, you idiot.¬† That was not an angel, but a criminal mastermind assassin.¬† And you are now officially not fit to stand trial as a witness against him.¬† I imagine that is what you wanted all along." BUT, this is a movie, so the angel angle makes way more sense - is more dramatic, don't you think?) ...... The Confession Ritual - that only works if the person who comes to give confession actually feels like he has done something wrong, has something to feel guilty about.¬† "I was just saying..."¬† "it's just a recipe, right?".... No. ... Good to know, so that one might not get, .. stoned. ..... Umm, so as long as it is consensual, it is still not OK, huh?¬† That makes sense. But now, they who feel no guilt, why would they go to confession? And so, I think the whole confession ritual is problematic. Gluttony, is very very bad.¬† But who believes this? See, Deuteronomy 20:21-22, kjv. ..... And so there are, I think, many Catholic congregations, where people feel good about themselves, and cannot think of what they ought to be confessing about, since they know not the Law (of Moses).¬† "Brother, have you tithed, .. this week?"¬† Sure, Cesar may call it racketeering... but really, ... it's for a good cause, right?

text: The known story of this guy is that he was an FBI informant, the reality is, he wasn't. In the documentary "The US vs James L Bulger" experts explained that would of bee impossible just based on his file. For someone who was allegedly an informant as long as he was, his file should of been over 20,000 pages long, instead it was under 800 pages. Bulger said through the prison glass he was never a rat and he got information and leeway to commit his crimes from the FBI by paying them off. The FBI knew this information would get out and make the whole department look crooked so they fabricated (allegedly) the story of him being an informant.

text: I just saw this one last night. If you're serious about the art of film and stuff, listen to this review if you're thinking about seeing it and obviously this is just my opinion, but here goes anyway. This movie isn't very good. The cast is stacked throughout with male actors who give solid performances but I doubt anyone didn't expect that. For how intimidating and violent the film is advertised, the movie actually has a rather monotone mood throughout. This leads into the key and most crucial aspect of this films downfall to me which is that there is no main character in the film to tie yourself too. For it being portrayed as all about whitey bulger, the film actually isn't centralized around any one character. It's no ones story and without that in a film, there's little to deliver other than facts. Rotten tomatoes gave it a 78. Trust me when I say that I strongly believe the cast has to do with that success. Personally I'd have put it at about a 68, myself and no higher.

text: Johnny Depp portrays the vulgar violent ruthless alpha male gangster real well. His acting was incredibly real -- stellar performance. His laughter is exactly like mine except I tried not to laugh so often and hide it, not show that real side of me. Anyway, the scenes shows mostly his vulgar side, such as in the bedroom of his best friend. He doesn't even knock on the door and politely ask. Instead, he acts like he was king of that house and turns the locked door knob several times. When she opens the door, she sees him and tries to wedge the door in between them. He stops her from doing that. He enters into her private bedroom without permission and starts a mini conversation with her. He caresses the side of her face and he massages her throat. She, of course, didn't think highly of his massage. She felt more like he was going to choke and strangle her and feared him. He loved it! You can tell right there and then he was summing her up. As he leaves, he turns around, smiles, and looks at her, expressing his envious at what a catch his best friend has --- the ideal trophy wife who won't retaliate against him(as like his current woman).

text: They try too hard to make him look like a one dimensional psychopath who never has any fun in this film. He is more like a comic book villain than a person. It's like he exists purely to cause misery, not to enrich himself and live a nice life. He was a guy who made good money and had connections with important people (apparently he was an FBI informant for years) that allowed him to run a criminal enterprise. He was in a world where killing happened as part of the game.    Does this mean he goes around like a monster every waking minute? Why is he made out to be a devil, whereas other mob movies show the mobsters enjoying the fruits of their labour? This movie is tacky and unrealistic IMO.   Pablo Escobar was responsible for far more death, torturing, misery, and evil and he isn't portrayed like this. It is so weird that it makes it uncomfortable to watch because they totally dehumanize Whitey. They make him look like someone who gets no pleasure from anything in life, but in causing pain, just like some evil comic book villain stereotype.
